lus, Matthew L. Jones argues that this drive for moral therapeutics guided important developments of early modern philosophy and the Scientific Revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  avirtue, leibniz, pascal, descartes, philosophy, scientific revolution, consolation, purpose, suffering, meaning, morality, ethics, assurance, comfort, science, religion, faith, spirituality, cognition, personal growth, mathematics, discipline, nobility, calculus, arithmetical triangle, geometry, moral therapeutics, history, disproportion, truth, expression, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226409566423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226409566/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles